{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:183","names":{"en":"Rulers of Mataram","tr":"Mataram Sultanları","ar":"Salātīn Matārām"},"country":["BN","ID","MY","PH"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"183","atlas_name_en_original":"The Rulers of Mataram","parent_tribe":"Mataram Cava hanedanı","ethnic_origin":"Cavalı (Müslüman)","capital":"Kotagede → Kerta → Plered → Kartasura","region_primary":"Orta ve Doğu Cava","regions_all":"Kotagede; Kerta; Plered; Kartasura; Cava","geographic_zone":"Güneydoğu Asya","predecessor":"Demak Sultanlığı / Pajang","successor":"Surakarta Susuhunan'ları ve Yogyakarta Sultanları (1755 Giyanti Antlaşması)","government_type":"Sultanlık","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Rulers of Mataram established Java's most powerful Islamic state, laying the foundations of Islamic political tradition on Southeast Asia's most populous island. Sultan Agung's resistance against the Dutch and the Javanese culture-Islam synthesis are the defining elements of this era. Weakened by Dutch interventions, the sultanate was divided into Surakarta and Yogyakarta by the 1755 Treaty of Giyanti.","importance_level":"Yüksek","capital_lat":"-7.6","capital_lon":"110.49","century_start":16,"century_end":18}}
